<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-02-14T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-02-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="547" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d547">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/667.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Mexican Chargé
                                    d’Affaires</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-02-14"><hi rend="italic">February 14,
                                    1911</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 418.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the
                            receipt of your note [No. 699] of the 23d ultimo, communicating to the
                            Department a report received by your Government that the rebel leader,
                            José de la Cruz Sánchez, has entered American territory at the head of
                            20 men, to buy arms and ammunition which are sold to them freely by
                            traders.</p>
                        <p>In reply I have the honor to inform you that your note has been
                            communicated to the Department of Justice.</p>
                        <p>Accept [etc.],</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington
                            Wilson.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>